📘 E. Add Modulo 10 — Complete Notes (Contest Ready)
🔥 1. Core Operation
𝑎𝑖=𝑎𝑖+(𝑎𝑖 mod 10)

👉 Only the last digit matters

🧠 2. Key Intuition (Most Important Part)
👉 Numbers behave in 2 completely different ways
🔹 Type 1: Numbers ending with 0 or 5
Last Digit	Behavior
0	No change possible
5	One step → becomes multiple of 10

Example:

15 → 20 → 20
10 → 10

👉 Final state = multiple of 10 (fixed)

🔹 Type 2: Numbers NOT ending with 0 or 5

Example:

6 → 12 → 14 → 18 → 26 → 32 ...

👉 Pattern:

Cycles through: 2 → 4 → 8 → 6
Every 4 steps → +20
🚨 CRITICAL OBSERVATION

👉 These two types can NEVER meet

Type 1 → stuck at multiples of 10
Type 2 → never reaches multiple of 10
🎯 3. Approach
🔹 Step 1: Handle numbers ending with 5
if(i % 10 == 5) i += 5;

👉 Convert all 5 → 0 type

🔹 Step 2: Check if any number ends with 0
if(i % 10 == 0) zero = true;
🔸 Case A: If ANY number ends with 0

👉 Then:

All numbers must already be equal
Because they can’t change anymore
if (count(begin(v), end(v), v[0]) == n)

✔️ YES
❌ NO

🔸 Case B: No number ends with 0

👉 All numbers are in cycle type

🔹 Step 3: Normalize all numbers

Bring all numbers to last digit = 2

while(i % 10 != 2) {
    i = i + (i % 10);
}

👉 Why 2?

Every cycle passes through 2
Makes comparison easier
🔹 Step 4: Check modulo 20
diff % 20 == 0

👉 Because:

Cycle adds 20
So valid differences = multiples of 20
⚡ 4. Final Logic Summary
✅ Possible if:
All numbers become equal (for 0-type)
OR
All numbers fall into same mod 20 group
💻 5. Code (Clean + Explained)
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

void solve() {
    int n;
    cin >> n;
    vector <int> v(n);

    bool zero = false;

    // Step 1: preprocess
    for(int& i: v) {
        cin >> i;

        // convert 5 → 10 type
        if(i % 10 == 5) i += 5;

        // check if any becomes multiple of 10
        if(i % 10 == 0) zero = true;
    }

    // Case A: contains multiple of 10
    if(zero) {
        // all must be equal
        if (count(begin(v), end(v), v[0]) == n)
            cout << "YES" << endl;
        else
            cout << "NO" << endl; 
    }
    else {
        // Case B: cycle type

        // Step 3: normalize to last digit = 2
        for(int &i : v) {
            while(i % 10 != 2) {
                i = i + (i % 10);
            }
        }

        // Step 4: check modulo 20
        sort(begin(v), end(v));

        for(int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            int diff = v[i] - v[i-1];

            if(diff % 20 != 0) {
                cout<<"NO"<<endl;
                return;
            }
        }

        cout<<"YES"<<endl;
    }
}

int main() {
    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while(t--) {
        solve();
    }
    return 0;
}
